reviews.text:
Love this Hawaiian style poke spot which really lets the seafood shine! They have big portion sizes and limited topping options that complement the fresh fish. We got our food to go and it still tasted delicious after driving back to Seattle. Highly recommend the tuna and mac salad!

Parking lot out front with plenty of spaces.

Step aside Jimmy Johns, Ono gives a whole new meaning to Freaky Fast. Poke was ready by the time I had swiped my card. This is some of the best poke you can find in Washington hands down. Definitely a little pricey but it is worth every cent. Truly authentic Hawaiian style poke and the Mac salad might give you super powers. Definitely will be coming back. Pic is of the spicy salmon and Hawaiian albacore with Mac salad as the side

Great Hawaiian poke!  Customer service was amazing, got a run down of everything, along with the ability to sample before picking my protein.  Everything was so fresh and packed with flavor!  You can’t go wrong with any of the choices. Can’t wait to go back!

Wish I knew of this place sooner! The poke is absolutely fantastic. I’ll need to visit place more often for when I’m in the mood for poke.

The food was fresh and I didn’t have to wait long for my order either. I like that their menu is limited so I’m not overwhelmed with choices. Definitely recommend getting Poke here if you’re in the area.

Pretty authentic poke comparable to ones I had in Hawaii.  A bit pricey but understandable. a larger portion for side/rice would be nice.

Minus one star for the weird 1 dollar credit card fee which is pretty high… even food trucks don’t charge this pls reconsider

Ono Authentic Hawaiian Poke.description: Ono, named for Oahu-born owner Steven Ono, is a seafood lover’s dream in Edmonds, offering possibly the highest-quality poke in the Seattle area on a menu that rotates depending on what’s fresh. Just as importantly, the restaurant uses a light hand with flavorings so you don’t lose the flavor of the fish itself, whether you’re eating salmon dressed with ponzu or a spicy ahi bowl.

Cafe Juanita.description: Kirkland’s Northern Italian fine dining mainstay offers several excellent seasonal tasting menus, including pescatarian, vegetarian, and vegan options. Chef Holly Smith’s omnivorous tasting menus include dishes like Anderson Valley lamb chops with turnip gratin, while a vegan tasting menu features meat-free marvels like green garlic soup with fava bean toast.

reviews.text:
Absolutely the best experience we have had dining in Seattle.

We arrived for our reservation at 5:15pm, on a Tuesday, and waited less than a minute for our table overlooking the kitchen. We asked for a bottle of champagne to be on the table when we arrived, since we were celebrating.

Service was VERY attentive, informative, and had great recommendations. The food was unbelievably delicious, well seasoned, and cooked to perfection.

Really great place to relax and eat a great meal. I will definitely be returning and recommending.
We went here for our anniversary and the food was incredible! One of the best steaks I've ever had. It was cooked just right and amazing flavor. The appetizers were fantastic as well.

Environment is very energetic. Service was outstanding. Drinks were reasonably priced and tasty. We had the OF, a bottle of wine, and the espresso martini. The grits and the potatoes were 10/10!! The steaks were in the mid 3 category..?! That’s ultimately what caused a 4 instead of a 5… if I leave a place thinking my grill could prepare a better steak.. it just doesn’t deserve 5 stars.. the dessert was above average 🙌🏽 - will probably forego trying again, but I recommend.

If you like your steak, this is the place.  Absolutely buzzing on the Friday night we visited.  We arrived early for our reservation, but were able to sit at the bar and enjoy a glass of very decent house Chardonnay.  The hanger steak was sublime (cooked a perfect medium-rare).  Our second time here, and we'll be back soon.

An awesome dinner and an overall great experience.The waiter was very welcoming and made us feel home, the atmosphere was also nice, maybe a bit too noisy but it was ok.

The food was AWESOME! The meat well cooked and very tasty, the selections of beers and alcohol was excellent and the dessert was great.

What to say, a great dinner!

FlintCreek Cattle Co.description: Chef Eric Donnelly’s Greenwood steakhouse is one of the best in the city, serving simple 21-day dry-aged Washington steaks that are perfectly grilled and buttered, with options for filet mignon, New York strip, Delmonico, and tomahawk. Flintcreek Cattle Co. also stands out for incorporating game meats like elk and wild boar into the menu. Don’t overlook the stunning vegetable dishes amid all this meat, though. The drinks from the full bar are well-balanced, and dessert’s worth saving a little room for too.

reviews.text:
Tonight we enjoyed the Chef’s Choice. Before dining I read all the reviews. Needless to say I was very intrepid about being a guest at this establishment. Yet, after actually eating there I have to say, WOW! My palette was delighted with full flavors distinctive and nuanced like I was at my boyfriend’s family home. His mom was Lebanese! As well, I am a Chef.
The ambiance was comfortably classy & clean. The service was very kind, loving, & professional….it was my birthday “eve” celebration. (They made me feel special.)
The full body, dry, red, Lebanese bottle of wine, was excellent with our meal.
My only wish? More Lamb! I know it’s expensive…..charge for it. I LOVE it❣️
Thank you for a perfect dining experience. ♥️

The restaurant staff and the service is excellent. The food let us down from an overall good experience.
We ordered 3 appetizers, 1 entrée and all of them were mediocre. I'm sure good quality ingredients were used looking at the restaurant setup. But the dishes just didn't have the flavor or taste. Dishes were mild and bland.
And the pita bread was underwhelming. Served cold and felt store-bought. Affected all the other dishes as well.
The seating is indoor and gets noisy during rush hours. If you're planning to have a quiet time, maybe not the place at the peak times.
Easy to find street parking nearby. No outdoor seating.

The food is excellent. It's better if you make a reservation. They were extremely busy. By 7:30  pm they didn't have the most popular items on the menu available. Our waitress was rude. The other waitress that help us was hustling but still nice, meaning with manners. Thanks God the rude waitress left. With all this, we understand they are short on personal and it was a Friday night. The food is definitely worth it. We learned the lesson and we're either going back on a less busy day or earlier.

This Lebanese restaurant is definitely a gem in Ballard! A lot of vegetarian options, very balanced flavor and texture!

The beet tahini is surprisingly refreshing and tasty. - 5/5

Hummus bi tahini has so soft and creamy texture, with strong but balanced herb smell, and mild cumin flavor. Love it. 5/5

Pita is complimentary with other fish orders. Each dish comes with 2 half pitas. Pita is thin and a bit dry. You can smell not too much butter. 4/5

Lamb Kifta doesn’t smell too lamb, that’s good if people don’t like strong lamb smell. Herb is super with the minced lamb! Soft and juicy with pita. 4/5

Love the interior design of the restaurant, very old fashioned.

Delicious Lebanese food!! Wow, I can’t believe we’ve lived in Ballard for so long and just now discovered this place. It’s a true neighborhood gem. Nice service and cozy ambience, though the restaurant itself is quite outdated and old, it adds to the charm!

Cafe Munir.description: Owner Rajah Gargour’s Lebanese background informs the food at this intimate Ballard restaurant, which is particularly friendly to vegetarians with its many plant-based meze. The small plates of lentils ground with roasted garlic, house labneh, and sweet pears in savory tahini always impress, and the chef’s choice (or “Rajah roulette,” as the restaurant has called it) dinner on Sunday makes for one of the city’s best dining experiences, brimming with uncommon and seasonal dishes.

reviews.text: We came for the wine bar and everything was fantastic. It's an intimate space with an outstanding wine menu and excellent food options. Everyone was super friendly too. We will absolutely be back. You should make reservations if you're coming for the restaurant. Weekends are a multicourse tasting menu, but there's excellent food served during their wine bar too. Strongly recommend!

Simply the best specialty butcher in Seattle.  High quality craftsmanship and a wide range of choices make this place stand out.  The service is exceptional and they always patiently answer questions even when the line is out the door, as it sometimes is.  Creative new sausages, pates, and unusual cuts of meat make this place a culinary adventure.  The price is very fair given that they source their meat from local, humane farmers, not factory farms.  Give them a try!

During my visit in Seattle a good friend took me for diner to this place. The venue, ambience and experience was amazing. I enjoyed a five course meal there including their signature pate. It was outstanding. The staff was super friendly and the chef came after diner asking if we enjoyed the food - we did! Highly recommended. You probably need to reserve ahead of time to enjoy their fanatic menu.
One of my favorite places I've ever eaten at...period. The sunday tasting menus are not to be missed. The passion they have for their food and wine is evident with every single course.

YOU MUST GO TO THE WINE BAR! NOW! Wow, what an amazing dining experience. The space is cozy and we were seated at the window. Only gripe was that a place to stick your feet in front of the stool would be a welcome addition. We started off with a bottle of Reynvaan that was a great price with only a bit of markup (excellent bottle as always). The Somm Nick was delightful and very knowledgeable. Katie was great at front of house. The pate with smoked plum jam was a highlight and the burger with maple and bacon was decadent and an umami bomb. Super rich! The London Royale was cooked perfectly and packed with beefiness. This is a must buy in my opinion. We let the kitchen choose a sausage for us…andouille…and it was great with nice spice. We didn’t save room for dessert. Epic meal all around. Seriously some of the best food in Seattle. Epic meal.

Beast and Cleaver.description: London native Kevin Smith has built a cult following over the last few years for Beast and Cleaver, turning the Ballard spot into one of the city’s top destinations for carnivores. During the day, the business is simply an excellent whole-animal butcher shop serving house-made sausages and pates, local and imported steaks, and chicken, duck, and pork products, with plenty of expert recommendations for what to do with unusual cuts. On weekends, the celebration of meat kicks up another gear, when it turns into an exclusive tasting-menu restaurant under the moniker the Peasant, which serves dishes like koji-aged beef and duck confit with Yorkshire pudding waffles.

reviews.text:
My friend and I went here, ordered just about one of everything off the menu, and can definitely say EVERYTHING is top notch amazing. The chicken has light and crispy Filipino-style breading, fried to perfection with all the juice still intact. Paired with a smattering of authentic Filipino fusion sides, and complemented with friendly staff, the hype around The Chicken Supply is legit 🐥🇵🇭
Make sure to place your order for the next day at 9/9:30 PM the night before!

Visiting Seattle and I had to give it a try. I'm from the south so I know about good fried chicken and this place is legit. The fear with fried chicken is that it could easily be overcooked and dry, but this chicken was cooked perfectly.  It was flavorful and juicy. Do yourself a favor and get the chicken stick and a thigh or drumstick. They both have different textures and both are yumm. Also had garlic rice, collard greens, and monggo. Everything was a hit with me and the family. Plus they gave us extra chicken cause they said the thighs were a little small. That's awesome customer service right there. Highly recommended!

Wow. Best fried chicken I’ve ever had, and I grew up in the south. Super crunchy, flavorful, and juicy. Sides were 10/10 as well, especially the marinated veggies. Get the spicy chicken!!!!! We’ll be back for sure!

I did not even know there was this much hype here. On a Tuesday, they sold out of all chicken by 6:38pm. This Filipino fusion restaurant. I got all the chicken options Wings $3,  Drum $4, Thigh $7, and Stick $8. After tax and tips it came to $30. The spicy sneaks up on you and is spicier than Sriracha (The rooster sauce). The crispiness of the fried chicken is thin, but it is a refreshing taste. The chicken are tender and not dry :) Once you have the stick, you'll understand why its worth the $8. its convenient, easy to share, and you can just be like a kid and treat it like popsicle. I recommend the Monggo Bean to counter the spicy chicken. The Cold Pancit taste literally like a salad and nothing like what you have in mind for Filipino pancit. I recommend you to come early because this place is popping. Their restroom is not called restroom lol

Best fried chicken you could get in Seattle. Don't think, just go order and eat. They open at 4pm and will be sold out mostly by 4.30pm. However, you could order online and schedule pickup for any time in the evening.

The Chicken Supply.description: This casual Filipino fried chicken shop in Phinney Ridge was Eater Seattle’s pick for Best New Restaurant in 2022, and one of Eater’s favorite fried chicken restaurants in the country. The gluten-free batter on the chicken — wings, drumsticks, or 10-inch-long cylinders of white meat on sticks — crackles under the teeth and has the puffy texture of Rice Krispies or Frosted Flakes. The meat is packed with flavor from soy sauce and garlic. The restaurant’s owners, Paolo Campbell and Donald Adams, had wanted to start a fried chicken restaurant for years while working in fine dining, and now serve the fried birds with Filipino sides like collard greens served with coconut milk, marinated vegetables, and garlic rice.

reviews.text: Very good, wish I had looked into this place a lot sooner. Definitely want to go back and try more things. I had the prawns in red sauce and the Bien Salad. Both were delicious. The salad was simple but very good, wish I had ordered two of them! The prawns and rice was so good, nice garlic flavor. I asked for a 4 out of 5 on the spice level but it wasn't spicy at all so maybe they forgot but it was fine because it was so delicious and I added some spice at home. Very good food. The staff was super nice and helpful. Always looks busy when you go by it but they are very quick with making the food so don't worry about it. Not a lot of parking but with how quickly the food comes out it shouldn't take long to find a place to park. They do have some outdoor seating but seems like it's primarily a take out spot. Can't wait to go back!

Un Bien is Super Bien food 🤤! I've been here 3 times now and they have never failed me. The staff is soooo friendly, the cooks listen to all my favorite Spanish songs. No wonder the food taste so delicious. My go to always is the Bien Salad with Chicken Breast.
Super cool sandwich place. Feels like a food cart but with undercover outdoor seating. The sandwiches are large and delicious. We also tried Caribbean Salad (#17). It had a nice kick to it.

Ordered a #4 Palomilla Steak and a #27 Prawn Entree.

Both are fantastic! Tried Un Bien for the first time today. The 1.5k reviews did not disappoint. Great place to get a sandwich or a meal.

I will say, if you have to park, street parking in the neighborhood is the only option. So forewarning, you might have to walk a bit. That doesn't ruin the experience though.

Great food, super friendly cashier, will recommend!

*Lastly, the little plastic cup with the orange sauce is a new hot sauce they are sampling. If you want a little extra kick, not too spicy but a low mild heat, ask to see if they still have the little orange hot sauce.

Fast and no-frills counter service spot for a good sandwich. Heated patio seatings outside.

I arrived right after it opens so there was no line. I ordered the #1 pork shoulder sandwich and it was very juicy! What bothered me though is that the onions are undercooked and messed up with the overall texture. I kind of picked them out and ate first, then really enjoyed the sandwich.

Un Bien.description: We don’t need to get into the Shakespearean drama that resulted in the demise of the old Paseo, that legendary Caribbean sandwich shop run by Lorenzo Lorenzo. Suffice it to say that Un Bien, run by Lorenzo’s sons, is carrying on that legacy, and more importantly the marinade. Sweet, tangy, dripping from the slow-cooked pork (or chicken thighs), you could make a whole meal out of the marinade itself. The onions, meanwhile, are so tender and flavor-packed you should be able to get a sandwich that’s just onions, and in fact, you can. Don’t tell anyone but sometimes we’ll buy a little container of their black beans and eat spoonfuls in the car while we do errands.

reviews.text: I am not a big fan of tamales in general, but these are good. (I tried two vegan options.) They're also big, and well worth the $5 price. Good ingredients. Cool crew running the place too. If you like tamales, there's no reason not to come here.

I heard about this place from someone that lives nearby. Each visit to Seattle I enjoy trying new food places. Tamales just happen to be my very favourite Mexican fare so I had to give Freland Tamales a try. The tamale I purchased today was incredible. I don’t think I’ve ever had something as authentic as this tamale. The presentation stunning as the handmade effort is notable in a corn husk wrapped tamale with a beautiful red tie. The pickled vegetables are reminiscent of a Mexican restaurant I like in Las Vegas called Tacos Mexico. Taste of everything was delicious! Well worth a visit for exquisite Mexican cuisine at a low low price of seven bucks. Walk up order window. I believe you can also order ahead and pick up. The staff very friendly and courteous.

Not that it matters in the purchase however I read ahead of my visit the owners are deeply involved in the community and quite charitable.

I drove by this place many times and always saw the line.  Today my husband and I decided to try it out. I bought all three meat tamales and they were 6.50 each.  It was hot and smell so good. They also gave sour cream, pickled carrots,  and a green hot sauce (not sure what the name is). My husband likes the pork, I like the chicken the most, chorizo and cheese is my least favorite but it is still tasty.   We will be back again and try the sweet tamales.

Best tamales I've ever had. They are pretty huge, and stuffed with amazing fillings and love. Got a whole spread of flavors to try and they were all so good I can't really choose a favorite, but the jalapeño cheese, spicy shredded pork and spinach are definitely up there. They also have some vegan options and sweet dessert ones (sweet ones sold frozen only, so you have to make them at home). Also have an amazing beans rice and tamale lunch combo? Great great greaaat spot :)

The best tamales I’ve ever had. The chorizo/cheese is my favorite. Outstanding rice / beans as well. Been here a number of times since discovering them. Friendly staff, will definitely be back many times.

Frelard Tamales.description: From a farmers market favorite to a permanent tamale window near Green Lake, this popular Mexican spot from founders Osbaldo Hernandez and Dennis Ramey (with Hernandez’s parents helping run the operation) serves half-pound tamales packed with rich flavors. The salsa roja pork and the salsa verde chicken versions are as dreamy as you’d expect but don’t miss out on vegan and vegetarian options too, including tamales filled with sweet potato and mole and salsa roja and jackfruit. Everything comes with pickled onions and carrots and goes great with house-made agua de horchata. You can even stock up on bags of frozen tamales to steam at home.

reviews.text: 1st time here. Lots of menu items I've never heard of. Had the most different combination of tastes I've ever eaten in a restaurant. Did not like the om gang which is a curry but was more like a dill broth. Everything else was good especially the Crab fried rice and fried chicken wings. Outdoor seating available.

Portion is rather small, and I personally do not enjoy the BBQ Combo too much.
Tried the Monsoon cocktail (rotating cocktail), which was spicy mango Margarita (suggested by the staff). However, the drink did not taste or look like it and came quite slow after all main dishes are served 😅
You can select either chicken or pork for the BBQ combo, but not both. (Originally, I though the combo was chicken + pork, but actually it is papaya salad + protein).
Tried the pork, the portion of protein is really small, and quite dry and hard to bite.
The sauce is sweet and a great companion for the dish though, it really helps me to finish the dish.

Overall, I would say the price here is too high given the small portion of dishes. The prawn rice bowl my friend got literally had only 3-4 prawns in it and costs 15 dollars before tax 😅
The flavor itself is OK but not surprising.

Personally I might not give here another try, but might be good for large parties for small bites without reservations in the area.

I can't believe I forgot to leave a review for Pestle Rock! I came here about 3 months ago with 2 friends. We ordered many dishes to share. Everything was delicious and authentic. I also like that nothing was too spicy. The staff was very accommodating. I recommend this place. The only complaint is that if you sit by the door, it gets really cold when people are going in and out.

I love this place, it's solid and in my top 5 favorite restaurants in Seattle. If you've never had Isan Thai, this is the place to go. I've gone so many times, I always bring family and friends here when they visit and we've never been disappointed. My favorite dishes are the KHAO SOI -- this is closest to yellow curry dishes people that are at most American Thai restaurants, but it has egg noodle, chicken, pickled greens and crispy noodles, sooo good. It's not a very spicy dish, but for me it builds and by the end it's clearing my sinuses. For appetizers, the GAI YAANG (BARBEQUE CHICKEN) is great - nicely seasoned with a little sweetness, SAI UA (HOMEMADE THAI SAUSAGE) is my second favorite dish - has a little heat to it too. MUU PHA LO (STEW) is my second favorite entree and I almost always get it. It's so tender and not spicy, if anything a little savory sweetness, and is great to pour the juices over rice. Lastly, I always have dessert ROTI that is has cinnamon sugar with sweet condensed milk over it. It's crispy and sweet, plus I like to add a scoop of coconut milk.

For people used to chain restaurants that pop out 100 types of dishes, that are about large sizes and not really quality....

The dishes aren't overly huge, but appropriately portioned. It's definitely quality food, that focuses on fresh dishes made traditionally. They don't adjust spiciness, to preserve the way the dish is intended to taste. I recommend eating with family style with your group. I hope you enjoy this place as much as I do.

Nice restaurant in Ballard. I like the pork larb here. They really make it spicy :)

We got there 15 minutes before the kitchen closed. The waiter was really impatient to get our order, pushed the food out, including the ice cream (on sticky rice) while we were still having quite a lot of food on the table. At least they could have kept the ice cream in the fridge for us until we’re done with the food.

Pestle Rock.description: Among Seattle’s many neighborhood Thai restaurants, Ballard’s Pestle Rock stands out for using only local meat in its dishes and for staying laser-focused on Isan (Northeast) Thai cuisine. The flavors here are bold and unadulterated, with bright lemongrass and spicy chile enlivening the house-made sausage and funky, earthy shrimp paste covering the green beans and caramelized pork belly in the tua phad kapee. There’s no wrong pick from the list of “tossed” dishes, which come with lime juice and toasted rice powder, though the pork larb and nam tok (grilled wild boar collar) are particularly memorable. Try the wings at next-door sibling Sen Noodle Bar too.

The Walrus and the Carpenter.description: James Beard Award-winning chef Renee Erickson has had a major hand in the evolution of Seattle’s dining scene, and her Sea Creatures restaurant group owns many of Seattle’s top restaurants, from steakhouse Bateau to Westward on Lake Union. But Erickson has never let her original Ballard bar slip. The Walrus and the Carpenter serves several varieties of Washington oysters, seafood dishes like raw albacore tuna with Meyer lemon sauce and blood oranges, and snacks like beef tartare, beef shank terrine, and plates of sliced cheese, along with a long wine list and a thoughtful cocktail menu. The dining room is bright and airy, and the heated, covered patio sparkles with string lights. Be warned that you can’t make reservations at this perennial favorite; on the upside, this is one of the few Seattle-area date-night restaurants open on Mondays.

reviews.text: A welcome break from the normal cafe food options. The savory fry bread tacos were very good, and I really like the different topping flavor options there were. The staff is nice, and the fine in space is clean. A good place for a quick bite.

Very pleasantly surprised at the tastiness of the food considering its attached to a museum. Tried three different tacos as well as the sweet fry bread. All three tacos were delish (breakfast, pulled pork and bison). The fry bread was light, slightly crispy on the outside and a perfect transportation device for the well seasoned meats. Would definitely recommend to anyone in the area. Also you don’t have to pay museum entrance to have access as they are positioned before the formal museum entrance.

First time I've ever had Indian tacos. Specifically the braised bison meat taco this time. Also had their sweet frybread with cinnamon topping. And a cold brew coffee, but this didn't seem to have any particular feature from Native cuisine.

Definitely liked the bison taco. The frybread on which it's delivered reminds me of a kind of puffy pita. It's kind of a different twist on the handheld bread/tortilla+toppings/fillings formula that's universal around the world (tacos, pita, gyro, etc; I wonder if there is a concise culinary term encompassing this idea?). Bison meat is closest to beef out of the common meats eaten in the US, but it's definitely its own flavor. I liked it; it was well made. The toppings were kind of generic, some greens, radish, etc.

The sweet frybread appears to be the same bread base as the taco, but with sugar and cinnamon added on. There are many many topping choices other than cinnamon, but it was recommended to me. Definitely good, reminds me of sweetbreads you get elsewhere.

The cold brew was your typical cold brew.

The service was good, the host was good at recommending items to me, as this was the first time I've ever been in a Native taco place.

The space is amazing during good weather. They open the huge huge class wall to the outdoors, so you get a light filled space but also shade if you want it. And you're in the modern museum building. Really good architecture going on here.

Overall, I rate it 4 stars. It's good, worth the visit, a good choice if you want something fast and not expensive, a good space, and bonus points for serving a cuisine (Native American) that's not widely available.

Can't give it 5 stars because the food, while good, is not amazing. At no point did I feel that "wow".

The fry bread is delicious and fresh ! I really enjoyed the fry bread tacos and dessert fry bread. This location was really nice! I loved how they had literally the side of the building tilted open to let in fresh air. Very unique! Parking wasn’t that great but for the area it was expected.

First time having fry bread and it was delicious! The fry bread bison taco had such a comfort food quality with savory and flavorful warmth, definitely a new favorite of mine. The iced Chai was wonderfully spiced!

Off The Rez Cafe.description: Seattle’s only Native American-owned food truck opened its first restaurant in 2019 at the revamped Burke Museum on the University of Washington campus. Its menu is vibrant as ever, drawing on traditions that co-owner Mark McConnell’s mom shared from her upbringing on the Blackfeet Reservation in Browning, Montana. Indian tacos showcase fluffy fry bread topped with 12-hour-smoked pulled pork, braised bison, or vegetarian chili, while wild rice bowls feature the likes of braised bison and seasonal vegetables; pair it all with house-made cedar blackberry tea. You can dine in, sit at benches outside while you eat, and order takeout or delivery online.

reviews.text: One of the best pizzas in Seattle. Lupo have some really amazing flavor combinations on their specials, great basic pizzas, and an excellent crust. One of the stand outs for me is the vegan pizza. I am by no means a vegan, but dang, it is so flavorful and I will gladly order it every time and it is probably the best vegan pizza I’ve ever had anywhere. The service is always great and the atmosphere is nice and it’s perfect for a quick dinner or a date. Some of their ice cream specials have been top-notch and I will gladly go here again and again.

Very recently moved to Seattle with my wife and we are not a rare breed in that we love pizza.
I don't believe we have ever had sourdough pizza, but I saw Lupo on an Eater article, and had to try it.
The entire staff were pleasant and efficient.
We got the Caesar Salad (major kudos for them making the dressing it in house...you can really tell the difference) and we shared the "Uncle Don's".
The toppings perfectly complimented themselves and the sourdough crust was amazing: soft, kinda chewy, but charred a bit to add a bit of crunch as well.
We have found our pizza spot.

Ya know, there are a lot of great places to eat in Seattle but this spot, this spot is special. Such incredibly flavored food and delicious, natural wines. I think this might be my favorite restaurant in Seattle as it does not ever disappoint. The staff is friendly but doesn’t weirdly linger. The food is so flavorful, there’s not a thing on the menu I wouldn’t eat. Highly definitely absolutely recommend!

Lupo is such a lovely spot! Whether you’re grabbing takeout or sitting down, you won’t be disappointed by the delicious pizza and homemade ice cream. All of their pies are amazing but I think their margherita pizza is the best pizza I’ve ever had! And trust me when I say you can’t leave without some of their ice cream, especially the salty chocolate chocolate chip! We will be back soon.

All around delicious! Must try the Toasted House Sourdough! Their Caesar Salad is one of my top favorites…and I’ve had the real deal in the original Caesar’s Restaurant in Tijuana, MX.
Order your own pizza…sharing is nice, but the Cacio e Pepe is worth being greedy over.

Lupo.description: A growing number of excellent independent pizzerias in Seattle represent pizza nerds’ obsessive quests for the perfect pie, all a little different but often built on a base of local grains and seasonal toppings. Fremont’s Lupo stands out for its chewy, blistered sourdough pies with powerful but perfectly balanced flavors, like the burrata and soppressata pizza topped with sharp Calabrian chile peppers, hot honey, and grand cheese. Lupo also has a full bar and a solid list of natural wines. For a more casual experience with the same attention to the craft, check out the owners’ new sibling, Stevie’s Famous, in Burien.

result.adr_address: 1054 N 39th St, Seattle, WA 98103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Pocket-sized space specializing in handmade soba noodles, tempura & other Japanese specialties.

result.formatted_address: 1054 N 39th St, Seattle, WA 98103, USA
result.name: Kamonegi

reviews.text:
Very small cramped restaurant but their food and service makes up for it.
We ordered many different foods from the menu and every single one of them were flat out amazing. Especially all of their soba noodles, tempura and ducks were exceptionally good.
All the employees were very attentive, polite and helpful.
Highly recommend. I would definitely go back

Everything was light and tasty and nuanced. Flavor profiles were on point IMO. 👌Though I will say it’s a bit pricey for the amount of food my party got — I guess the service and the quality of the food make up the price though. the service was great and they were very accommodating (I was about an hour late to my res)! Thank you again! 🙏

Amazing local restaurant with great service and delicious food. The quality of the food is amazing and everyone was hospitable. Small shop, but we got some chef counter seats by arriving 10 minutes before they opened and the view into the kitchen was fun. They have a second restaurant/bar two doors over that serves some great sake and has a cute patio.

My wife and I were lucky enough to snag a table and enjoy a variety of the food from their menu.

The presentation and arrangement of each bite was carefully thought out and purposeful. Each item we tried was unique and delicious.

Definitely wanting to stop back in again soon!

We got to sit at the little bar in the corner of the building. It was a great intimate experience for an amazing lunch! Our bartender/server was incredibly friendly and helped me choose the sake and soba noodles that he thought I would like. And, oh boy, was he spot on. I was in heaven! The noodles are homemade and perfect! The broth was refreshing and had just the right amount of spice. I can't brag about this place enough. If I could give more stars, I would!!! This is an absolute must eat if you're in the area! Thank you for an amazing experience!

Kamonegi.description: Star chef Mutsuko Soma makes soba from scratch at this petite Fremont destination, which was one of Eater’s Best New Restaurants in America in 2018. Soma serves traditional soba shop dishes like seiro soba (cold with dipping sauce) and super-crunchy tempura, but also more creative dishes like soba with oysters and gochujang broth and oreo tempura accompanied by mini toasted marshmallows. Make a full night of it by sampling some sake and snacks at next-door sibling bar Hannyatou as well.

editorial_summary.overview: Polished operation with exposed-wood beams furnishing contemporary Indian cuisine.

result.name: Meesha

reviews.text: Food is delicious but the portions are kind of small! I also didn’t love that there was only one dish for each type of protein. Like they only had butter chicken, no other chicken dishes. Service was good and it’s cute inside!

Excellent meal. Excellent service. The drinks were incredible. The patio is so enclosed, it's like you're practically inside, so I felt a little weird about that, but the ambiance is nice. We had a wonderful experience overall and will be back.

Went here for dinner on a Friday night, and the place was packed! Good collection of cocktails and vegetarian food. Service was great, they were accommodating of our special requests. I tried the aloo tikki, kofta, paratha and kulcha. Aloo tikki was quite good, with balanced flavors. The kofta was also good, but nothing special for the cost on the menu. I liked the paratha more than the kulcha for sure. Overall, 3/5 food was decent but not worth the price, at least for vegetarians. Parking was easy to find right outside.

What a fun Indian fusion restaurant! Loved the atmosphere (sat on the back patio), very friendly service (s/o to Steven), and delicious food. There were a lot more options I wish I could have tried too! Definitely recommend.

Very good Indian restaurant, short but well chosen menu - our Connaught butter chicken and our Goan prawn curries were full of fresh ingredients, with rich, complex sauces and were beautifully presented. The staff were friendly, helpful and knowledgeable. Definitely a must for any fan of high quality Indian food.

Meesha.description: After building a strong following as a pop-up inside Fremont’s Pomerol, contemporary Indian specialist Meesha took over the space and became a full-fledged restaurant in 2020, complete with a covered and heated patio around the back. Chef Preeti Agarwal's can’t-miss dishes include rarah keema pao with expertly prepared ground lamb, fried Amritsari fish, and paneer in tomato sauce with black cardamom. The restaurant also features a robust drink menu with wine, beer, and original mocktails and cocktails like Mughal Empress, a creamy gin sour with pomegranate, rose, and sumac.

result.adr_address: 1421 NE Boat St, Seattle, WA 98105, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Globally inspired bites & gourmet pastries offered in a former boat-building facility with a patio.

result.name: Saint Bread

reviews.text:
Great little bakery with pastries, sandwiches hot and cold.  Lovely outdoor seating area.
Breakfast Sammie with Thai sausage was solid, wish the lemongrass flavor was stronger. Smash burger was delicious. Cinnamon sugar bread was good, I think the slice should be a bit thicker, cause it's amazing bread.

been here about a half dozen times.  baked items are tasty.  don’t expect big portions.  really a 4.5.  burger pictured was a smash burger, and the meat was too low of a ratio, i’d say.  mask policy just for ordering as all seating is outside.

Nice spot to grab breakfast or coffee. The baked goods are yummy and the coffee isn’t particularly good, but it’s not bad either. Staff is friendly. On the weekend there’s usually a small line, but it moves quickly. There’s some outdoor patio seating. It’s slightly off the beaten path, but worth visiting.

We went on a Saturday around 10 am. There was a small line to order and we found table on outdoor patio right away. Outdoor seating is has heaters that kept was cozy. I tried the fried egg sandwich, Avocado toast and mushroom galette and really enjoyed all of them. The Orange miso coffee cake was also delectable.

Amazing coffee and delicious bakery items. Outside seating in a covered area as well as open seating with uncovered area overlooking the water. They also have other light meal options. If you have children they also have highchairs, and their bathrooms are very clean! Visit this sweet little spot near the UWMC!

Saint Bread.description: Calling Saint Bread a bakery is like calling Notre Dame a church. Yes, it is a bakery — a damn good one that has great cardamom knots, black sesame seed rolls, and Norwegian-style school buns. But what Saint Bread really specializes in is merging Seattle’s many different culinary cultures. You can get a breakfast sandwich on Japanese melonpan to add a layer of sweetness above the egg, or a smashed cheeseburger topped with “hoisin island dressing,” or an okonomiyaki-style Spanish tortilla. Its out-of-the-way location on Jensen Marina belies its importance; eat the whole menu and you’ll get a sense of what Seattle cuisine is all about.

result.adr_address: 3506 Stone Way N, Seattle, WA 98103-8924, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Korean-fusion steakhouse offering Asian-Northwest eats amid handmade wallpaper & communal seating.

result.formatted_address: 3506 Stone Way N, Seattle, WA 98103, USA
result.name: Joule

reviews.text: Great food, cool atmosphere, and friendly staff! For two people, we shared the scallion pancake, smoked tofu, crispy cauliflower, and the burger, and everything was delicious, though lacking in familiar Korean flavors. Maybe it was the dishes we got, but the most Korean thing was the side dish of kimchi we ordered. Regardless, all was very tasty! The mushrooms on the smoked tofu were a stand-out, and the curry sauce mayo for the cauliflower was phenomenal. The burger was simple but easily one of the best I've ever had! The meat grind was heavenly and all the ingredients were fresh and super high quality. Both desserts we tried, the hummingbird cake and the cheesecake, were decadent and the perfect mix of sweet and savory. I'd definitely come back to try more - maybe I can be convinced of the Korean element of the fusion.

It's possibly the best meal I've had. It's the best part of Korean food mixed with other parts of the culinary world. Influences are everywhere in each dish but to dwell on them would be a disservice because it's a whole new thing.
They have small, shareable plates. I recommend the beef tartar, Korean rice cake, and the short rib steak.
10/10 service and atmosphere.

Happened upon this restaurant on the Eater 38! I don’t rely much on Google when visiting such a tourist forward city, so always thankful of articles like that. This restaurant was outstanding!!! Dishes were vibrant and creative and seasoned so incredibly well. The wine list was creative and local and each wine we tried was delicious! Our server Madeline was attentive and thoughtful and even brought a birthday dessert when we were too full to order one. 10/10. Really really recommend the seam buns and rice cakes!

Massive disappointment. There is "fusion" which bring out flavors that didn't mix before for a new experience and then there is the disaster fusion where nothing is done right. Korean food is completely bastardized, even when you try to accept it as an homage. I wasn't expecting things to be authentic but after tasting the kimchi and scallion pancakes, I was "done". The chef was banking on customer ignorance on Korean food rather than trying to evolve it with fresh angles.

As my pictures show, we had a variety of dishes. Every one of them a disappointment, either bland or over spiced without the balancing flavors Korean food has. Also Korean spices and style do not go well with certain vegetables and ingredients and all sorts of lines were crossed to create something that visually may look interesting but complete bastardizes the balance of Korean flavors. Perhaps the only exception was the steak but that was just good meat cooked well.

Joule tries to do too much. If it wasn't for the swanky atmosphere, I would've notched it down to 1 star. Not returning even if the food served free.

We had a reservation for a Wednesday evening at 5:30 and were one of the only people in there- I love that but if that's not your jam, it gets a lot busier later in the evening. Our service was exceptional, the waiter gave us plenty of recommendations, our water was frequently filled, and food came out quickly but not too quickly that our dishes felt rushed.

We ordered the rice cakes with chorizo and they were perfection- if you are thinking about them but aren't sure, just do it!

The scallops had a really flavorful sauce underneath and they had an perfect crust on one side and a beautiful tender inside.

My boyfriend loves steak so we ordered the grass fed rib eye. I am not the hugest red meat girl and this was still a phenomenal dish. The whole peanuts complement the flavors well and the mint leaves helped cool down my mouth from those Thai chilis! Please note that I am not a fan of spicy food but this way still phenomenal!

The vibe inside is really cute, they have a custom made wall paper, and if you are lucky enough to have a view of the kitchen you can see the chefs hard at work!

Can't wait to go back!

Joule.description: Chefs Rachel Yang and partner Seif Chirchi offer simple, refined dishes at their Korean-influenced Fremont restaurant, from smoked mackerel kedgeree and succulent kalbi short rib over grilled kimchi to smoked tofu with mushrooms and geoduck black rice modeled after paella. With easygoing service and an inviting, open space as well as a patio, the restaurant provides a special night out sans pretension. Sit at the bar and watch chefs plating dishes while you sip on one of Joule’s creative cocktails, like the Jalisco Campfire, which blends a lapsang souchong-infused tequila with lime and Thai chile agave.

result.adr_address: 2968 Eastlake Ave E, Seattle, WA 98102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Upscale Japanese spot serving sushi & cocktails in an elegant, modern space with an open kitchen.

result.formatted_address: 2968 Eastlake Ave E, Seattle, WA 98102, USA
result.name: Sushi Kappo Tamura

reviews.text: Incredible sushi of course, but if you have a chance for the oyster, definitely get those - you won't regret it. The interior is crisp and warm. We tried almost everything on the menu. Also got to see Chef Shota drop in at the bar for a bite, which was pretty exciting for this fangirl. The only thing was that the wait for food was a bit long (each time we put in a sushi order), I think it was a busy night, but we weren't in a hurry so still had a very enjoyable experience.

Really good sushi. The service was pretty impeccable. Really elegant space with lovely plate presentation. I had the black dragon roll and a sushi combo. It was all well executed and clearly of the highest quality. My only gripe is that it felt like something was missing? Maybe in the rice. Some of the nigiri pieces were underwhelming especially given the freshness of the fish. Overall it was great. Just lacking a little oomph.

The sushi was real good and real good for the price! However, the atmosphere wasn't amazing (though looking at the chef seats it could have been - reserve there if atmosphere and service are high priority for you). The waiter was knowledgeable, but we definitely got not as good service as some of the folk who looked more traditional (we have dyed hair, etc). We did not like the sake selection when we were there, but the lychee margaritas are incredible!!

Very good food and service. I like the black  cod with miso the best. Can’t describe its taste with words, just try it! The five course menu also has great value. Though they make steamed egg counts as one course, but the other will also make you stuffed.

Incredible experience.  They grow as much as they can on their rooftop garden.  The American Unagi is something special that you can’t easily find here in Seattle.  The homemade mochi and matcha ice cream top off an exquisite meal.

Sushi Kappo Tamura.description: Of all the sushi chefs in Seattle, Taichi Kitamura may know the most about local fish, and at his Eastlake destination, Sushi Kappo Tamura, he provides an experience you couldn’t replicate in any other part of the country. He sources seafood, sometimes exclusive items like bairdi (aka tanner) crab, from Pacific Northwest producers like Taylor Shellfish and Skagit River Ranch as well as individual fishers, and grows some of the restaurant’s produce in a garden on the roof. You can taste the results by way of a full a la carte menu featuring sushi and hot dishes as well omakase showcasing seasonal specialties, perfect with a seasonal sake flight.

result.adr_address: 2576 Aurora Ave N, Seattle, WA 98109-2206, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Landmark fine-dining destination (since 1950s) offering Pacific NW fare in a midcentury-modern home.

result.formatted_address: 2576 Aurora Ave N, Seattle, WA 98109, USA
result.name: Canlis

reviews.text:
It’s a Seattle institution for a reason.

They really know what they’re doing here. Canlis in my opinion does more with a little less in comparison to other fine dining experiences. Is it pricey? Yes. Do you feel *managed*? A bit. The whole experience is tailored and they have pretty much every bite down to a science. You’re along for the ride.

Great bar area to gather before you dine. Every single person on the waitstaff moves with purpose and is incredibly knowledgeable. Wine list is expansive.

I won’t try to rob you too much of the experience.

If you’re on the fence, it’s worth it for a special occasion. Enjoy.

Amazing service. We were a party of 6 celebrating a birthday. From the time we parked ( valet parking) to finishing the dinner it was all so well managed. We spent about 3 hours at the restaurant and the way they explain the dishes was very interesting. We had a 6 course meal and they are flexible about accommodating vegetarian options too. One of the entree orders were wrong but I didn’t even bother to complain because the place has a great vibe and people. The location is fantastic and views amazing! Would love to visit again!

One of the most memorable dining experiences of my life! Exquisite attention to detail. Lovely staff. The food was mind blowing. I cannot recommend Canlis enough, for a fine dining experience. Our waiter, Jeff, was such a pleasure! He was attentive and walked us through the experience every step of the way.
I only wish I could come enjoy this regularly.

Is Canlis worth the hype? Yes. Everything from entering the building to the service being impeccable to enjoying dessert was superb. Be ready for a delicious, unrushed, and relaxing gastronomic experience.  Cocktails were creative and fantastic, and the wine list was more than plentiful.  Should this be a place for a special occasion? Absolutely! Be mentally prepared for pricing before you go so as to not suffer from "sticker shock" when the dreaded bill arrives, just a warning. Would I go back? Most definitely!

Canlis is always an experience - I’ve been a few times now, starting with the original menu a couple years ago, the Hawaiian themed summer party pop ups and now the tasting menu and it’s the service and attentiveness have always been top notch. Food this time was good and well portioned and paced between the 3 options you select and the 3 additional courses that come standard for the the table (amuse set, crab potato concoction and salad / bread this iteration).  At $165 a person + drinks it’s certainly not a regular outing but for a special occasion we had a good time and can recommend as a fancy splurge.

Canlis.description: Executive chef Aisha Ibrahim helms this Queen Anne icon, owned and operated by the Canlis family for over 70 years. The gorgeous restaurant overlooking Lake Union has won several James Beard Awards in recent years, including for its design and its wine program, and serves as a study in how to do fine dining without stuffiness, including excellent service whether you walk into the piano lounge or sit for a multi-course meal. Ibrahim energizes the historic establishment with a super-seasonal approach inspired by Japanese kaiseki cooking, and options might include duck with bitter chicory, celeriac, and blood orange; grilled sablefish with abalone, dashi, and daikon; and dark chocolate sorbet with koji and spruce tips.

result.adr_address: 13112 NE 20th St, Bellevue, WA 98005, USA
result.formatted_address: 13112 NE 20th St, Bellevue, WA 98005, USA
result.name: Dan Gui Sichuan Cuisine

reviews.text: Loved it! We have been going to another close by Sichuan restaurant for years now and it was our fav until we dined here! The portions are big, flavor is spot on and the service is fantastic. If you love sichuan cuisine, it is a must try!

My wife & I both love Szechuan cuisine and are very loyal customers to a Szechuan restaurant in the same area where we’ve been going for years. Today, we came here for the first time and we’re confused if we’d want to go to that other restaurant or not because that’s how much we loved the food here. The portions are big and the food is delicious and it cannot be any better. The service is amazing and our server was very polite and courteous. We ordered Herbal tea considering it is hot but it turned out to be cold tea cans. When she (our server) got to know about it, she asked us to try it for free (nice gesture on ber part) and it was very tasty. Overall, this is one of the best Szechuan restaurants we’ve ever been to. My only suggestion to them is to add Hot Tea (Jasmine or Oolong) to the menu. We’ll be back soon!

Update: We went there today for the second time and was happy to see that they've actually taken the above request for hot tea seriously as we were given hot tea as soon as we seated. The food was again delicious and our server was able to recognize us from our previous visit.

The food at this location is very authentic and flavorful.  The food will surprise you and definitely be an experience.  You cannot be shy about the heat and advanced ingredients they use in their dishes.  It is always filled with customers and definitely a place to try.  If you are a fan of Eater 38, it is on the list for great places to try.

The best Szechuan food I’ve ever eaten, and I’ve been to China. No kidding. The food here is superb. The quality is unmatched, the portions are huge, and the taste is phenomenal. I’ve eaten almost everything on their menu, including lamb, seafood, beef, chicken and veggie dishes. Everything is mouth watering good. Moreover, the service is top notch and everyone is super friendly. I’ve had two events here, and they were both a huge success, with all my friends concurring that this is the best Szechuan food in Washington. If ever there was a Chinese restaurant worth driving for, this is it. You’re guaranteed a first class meal, service, and atmosphere.

Ordered House Special Chow Mein w extra spicy.

Size: enough for a person to be full. Has chicken, shrimp, beef and cabbage.

Taste: actually not that spicy even I asked for extra spicy. But it tastes good so I think people who cannot eat spicy food can try the original version as well

Packaging: the to-go box is sturdy.

One small issue: the kitchen ventilator should do a better job to prevent the smoke from entering the dinning hall.

Dan Gui Sichuan Cuisine.description: Among the many Sichuan restaurants in the Seattle area, Bellevue’s Dan Gui stands out for its balanced flavors and consistently high quality. The cold plates, like the sliced pig ears shimmering with chile oil and the refreshing wood ear salad, are excellent with cold glasses of beer. The beef with vine peppers leaves the tongue buzzing with Sichuan peppercorn and jalapenos. No meal at Dan Gui is complete, however, without an order of tea-smoked duck, richly layered and cooked until just tender. Even the restaurant’s take on Chinese American dishes like orange chicken hit the spot.

result.adr_address: 903 19th Ave E, Seattle, WA 98112-4013, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Petite neighborhood eatery featuring traditional Laotian stews & sausages plus small plates.

result.formatted_address: 903 19th Ave E, Seattle, WA 98112, USA
result.name: Taurus Ox

reviews.text: Some of the most flavorful, delicious food we’ve had in Seattle! You MUST get the pork sausage, beef Jerky, and Burger for the table to share!! If you’re looking for something warm and homey the noodle soup and yellow curry were amazing choices. Truly can’t go wrong with the menu here, the chefs know what they’re doing!! Can’t wait to go back

Absolutely incredible laotian food that is tasty and memorable. I had the porl, the burger, the salad, and the dessert - everything was scrumptious but the pork was the clear winner: tasty, cooked properly, and just addicting. The burger was also super unique. Highly recommend this place!

So cute! New location is huge. Food is just as good as before, always get one of the iconic burgers to share. We are so full with an app and 2 entrees, highly recommend sharing. So sweet to see the increased capacity. We love Taurus Ox!

I can't wait to come back and try other dishes.
As imagine, this is in cap hill so quite the yuppie vibe. Price point and portion size is reasonable.

Service was attentive and food came out hot!
The phad Lao was made spicy with the peppers but overall the noodles weren't too spicy.

There is street parking around the area. Be prepared to walk from a couple blocks .

Excellent!!  The Lao Happiness Burger doesn't seem very Lao traditional but it is so delicious you have to try it.
Laab salad was great, Lao sausage was also great. Get the Jeow Bong side as well.  No Lao beer... Sounds like there are supply issues.

Taurus Ox.description: Often lumped in with food from neighboring Thailand when it makes the cut at all, the cuisine of Laos takes center stage at Capitol Hill’s Taurus Ox thanks to three chefs, Sydney Clark, Khampaeng Panyathong, and Jenessa Sneva, with strong Seattle dining pedigrees. The tiny counter-service shop recently upgraded to this full-service home, where dishes such as thom khem and chicken laap continue to benefit from local produce and a whole-animal approach to butchery. Don’t miss the Lao pork sausage, fragrant with lemongrass and lime leaf, or one of the city’s best patties, a smash burger made with pork jowl bacon and jaew tomato sauce. For another rare treat, pair it with a locally made sato, or Laotian rice wine, from Village Ghost.

result.adr_address: 615 19th Ave E, Seattle, WA 98112, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Stylish Vietnamese eatery offering contemporary dishes, such as its signature clay-pot catfish.

result.formatted_address: 615 19th Ave E, Seattle, WA 98112, USA
result.name: Monsoon Seattle

reviews.text:
The vegetarian and imperial rolls are very delicious. They're perfectly crispy and the taro idea is 👌
The papaya salad is kind of mild if you're used to eat original southeast Asian plates however for the western taste I think is very good. Catfish is a must. Overall a good place to eat 😋

Came during restaurant week. Pic 1: cocktails - Sayulita in the back and forgot the other one. Pic 2: drunken chicken and prawn curry. Pic 3: banana cake.
The drinks are great, pretty strong and complex in flavor. The drunken chicken is decently fried but the sauce is a bit on the sweet side. The prawn curry is tasty but very dry, as I usually prefer watery curry to go with rice.
We also ordered Bo La Lot (worth a try) and tofu fresh rolls (pretty average, good sauce though).
Overall a good meal for restaurant week price, but probably won’t come back for regular price.

Monsoon saved my birthday???

After a previously chosen restaurant didn't work out on my birthday, my family stumbled into Monsoon on a cloudy day.

Best. Mistake. Ever.

My previous experience with Vietnamese food was limited to pho and Bahn mi. Neither can be found on Monsoon's menu, but you won't miss them.

Starter:Salt and pepper wings were savory, tangy, delicious and fresh. The papaya salad was another excellent choice.

Mains: while the prawn curry was fantastic, the claypot catfish stole the show. The catfish is beautifully light and has a hint of peppery sweetness - goes great over rice. The crab fried rice was not stunning but sturdy, and drunken chicken disappointed with intense sweetness and overly heavy breading.

Dessert: We were not planning on dessert but got one free for my birthday 🎂 The waiter brought out banana cake with a sweetened coconut milk. The cake itself tastes like a nice banana bread, but it's the coconut milk that elevates it.

Monsoon's food is warm and comforting on a cold day.  Bring a date or a business associate to the beautiful dining space and cozy bar 🍸 Highly recommended!
My wife and I really enjoyed getting brunch here on the weekend. The food was delicious and shareable. The coffee cocktail had a potent kick. It was really easy and fast to get seated inside.

Went for Sunday brunch- no American fare on menu, instead, traditional Asian food on offer that was beautifully presented and tasty. Open space with lots of windows and two four-top tables on a small, but inviting patio. Friendly waitress. Street parking in this quieter part of Capital Hill.  We all enjoyed our dishes and it was great they had a shrub drink on the menu. Would return!

Monsoon Seattle.description: Eric and Sophie Banh’s Vietnamese restaurants — Monsoon, the original, and Ba Bar, the hip younger sibling — are some of Seattle’s best in part because they prioritize local ingredients. Though you can find casual favorites like imperial rolls with vermicelli on the menu, Monsoon focuses on fine dining with Chinese influences served family-style. Highlights include the wok-cooked Anderson Ranch lamb with chile and cumin, the catfish steamed in a clay pot with coconut juice, and a perfectly balanced green papaya salad with charred prawns. In addition to the Capitol Hill restaurant with its rooftop patio, Monsoon has a Bellevue location.

Spinasse.description: More than 10 years in, this romantic trattoria on Capitol Hill continues to entrance diners with food from Italy’s Piedmont region. The nest of delicate tajarin pasta with butter and sage sauce is a Seattle mainstay, but every dish from chef Stuart Lane is memorable. After a satisfying dinner at Spinasse, head to next-door sibling bar Artusi for a digestif and dessert, or stop by the bar another night for snacks like beef tongue with salsa tonnata (tuna sauce) and burrata with pomegranate seeds and toasted pistachios.

result.adr_address: 2350 E Union St, Seattle, WA 98122, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Sophisticated space offering international dishes, cocktails & a take-out option.

result.formatted_address: 2350 E Union St, Seattle, WA 98122, USA
result.name: COMMUNION Restaurant & Bar

reviews.text: Came here for a Sunday brunch. We had about 40 minutes of waiting as the place was packed. I tried the pork chop special which was pretty good. The spice and flavor was on point. It came with veggies which were great and grits which was creamy and complimented pretty well. The menu says that it comes with 2 eggs but later I had an additional charge of 3$ for the eggs so not sure. My wife got the Laotian sausage eggs Benedict which was pretty good as well and she enjoyed it. This is definitely a place to visit and I would come back for their dinner menu.  The service was pretty good and very fast. The place looks amazing and the vibe is pretty good 😊.

The starters and appetizers were delicious.  The deviled eggs had fun toppings and the sauce the clams were in was irresistible.  The cocktails were balanced and tasty.

The main entrees were good, but a little disappointing.  The jambalaya was tasty.  It had a good level of heat and depth of flavor.  The ginger chicken was juicy and light on flavor.  We all felt the entrees were nice but not special.  Their price is special though (read: pricey).

If the entrees had the same irresistible flavor as the clamb appetizer, I wouldn't be able to wait to come back.  As it stands, I am just glad I tried it.

Finally got to try this restaurant and it was so yummy. Luckily got a reservation and were seated promptly. The menu is a QR code which was easy to use and read. Got 4 appetizers and 3 mains which was enough for 4 people. The hood sushi was good, unique flavors and all. The shrimp toast was really good, a tad bit too done for me. Chicken wings has flavor but wish it was more juicy. Mac and cheese had a lot of flavor, better than expected. The mains were all amazing and unique in their own ways.

Hood Sushi: 4/5
Shrimp Toast: 4.5/5
Chicken Wings: 4/5
Mac & Cheese: 4.5/5
Catfish: 5/5
Jambalaya: 5/5
Garlic Chicken: 5/5

We had been waiting months to land reservations at a time that actually worked for our schedules, and were so happy to have it finally work out. Above all, the atmosphere of this restaurant can't be beat. So lively and a wonderful vibe. Truthfully, the appetizers were the best part of the meal: deviled eggs and shrimp toast. We ate them so fast we didn't even remember to take a picture. The fried oyster deviled eggs are a combo I didn't even know I needed in my life, but were amazing. From there we went with the pork chop and entree and Bayou Teche (special on menu). Both entrees were good, but not spectacular like the appetizers. We had the mac and cheese and collard greens for sides and, like the appetizers, were better than the entrees. Cocktails were reasonably priced, and good. Unfortunately by the time we got to dessert everything was already sold out, so didn't get to try anything. As others have said, the cost is a little pricey (even on Seattle standards), but 100% still worth going.

First I have to say the catfish and grits was one of the best dishes I’ve had! Unique and so flavorful. A lot of the appetizers were amazing as well (except the hood sushi wasn’t as impressive as I’d hoped). Overall I was impressed with the food but not as much the ambience. I felt like I had to shout to communicate with those at my table because the music and crowd was so loud and the service was on the slower side. They were also out of almost all the desserts which was a bummer. Pretty pricey for what it was but glad I was able to try this spot!

Communion Restaurant and Bar.description: Chef Kristi Brown — who made her name running the catering operation That Brown Girl Cooks — calls the food at her Central District restaurant “Seattle Soul.” At Communion, fusions like the Hood Sushi Bowl featuring fried catfish and seaweed salad come from Brown’s memories of shopping at Asian markets in the neighboring Chinatown-International District. But the dishes that shine brightest are her more traditional Southern ones, like a pork neck bone stew, with smoky meat simmered in umami-packed broth with lima beans. It’s hard to get a seat at this Eater Award-winner in the renovated Liberty Bank Building, a mixed-use affordable housing, retail, and resource hub for the Black community in the historically Black Central District. Make reservations weeks ahead, or show up right when the restaurant opens on a weekday to vie for a spot.

reviews.text: This was an experience, not a dinner. Wow. Every bite was like nothing I had tasted before (in a good way). Honestly, I can't remember the last time a dinner out felt like such an authentic cultural experience. This is a MUST try if you like Sushi. Thank you to the all the staff, our incredible server, and the best Sushi Chef I've had to privilege to encounter.

The Omakase is an absolute unforgettable experience. The staff is incredibly helpful. Knowledgeable and pleasant. They explain every meal every piece of sushi that they bring out to you and with each course things get more incredible, delicious, and amazing. This is an absolute must try while in Seattle. Write down by Pike. Place a very exciting, fun and engaging experience and culinary journey not to be missed!

It's hard to describe this restaurant in any words other than "incredible." I think I'm ruined for all other sushi going forward. Our chef Khota was an expert and did an incredible job during the entire Omakase experience. I highly recommend sitting at the Chef's Table (the bar) instead of reserving a table. It's much better to be able to talk to the chefs and watch your courses created in front of you. The sake selection here is excellent, they have some lovely options for those that enjoy an unfiltered variety. I will be back! ...eventually. The price is higher than many sushi places for a reason. You will not leave disappointed.

Come early and get the chef’s table if you are unable to get a reservation or just want sushi. The chefs are so nice and chatty and I had a great time talking story with them about sushi.

Everything was fabulous from the servers to the food. It came out fast and each dish had a short description. I highly recommend it after a trip to the market. A plus is seeing the sunset from the restaurant

Delicious, fresh seafood with a strong focus on locally sourced fish. Beautifully structured Omakase with details and care. The staff is discreet, welcoming, calm and provides lovely suggestions to curate the evening. Beverage selection covers high quality selection for every taste.

Sushi Kashiba.description: Seattle’s most influential sushi chef, Shiro Kashiba studied under Jiro Ono and brought edomae-style sushi to the city decades ago; he’s had a hand in some of the area’s top sushi restaurants, including Shiro’s in Belltown. Kashiba retired several years ago before making a triumphant return with Sushi Kashiba, this modern stunner in Pike Place Market. Diners rightly covet the first-come, first-served seats at the chef’s counter as they guarantee face time with Kashiba’s masterful team, but even if you can’t score a spot there, you should embrace the seasonal approach with an omakase menu, which will likely include local delicacies like geoduck. You can also explore octogenarian Kashiba’s legacy at restaurants like 2022 Eater Award-winner Takai By Kashiba, a Bellevue newcomer run by Jun Takai, one of Kashiba’s many proteges.

Cafe Campagne.description: This longtime Pike Place Market wonder from chef Daisley Gordon is well-regarded for its dedication to classic Parisian fare, served in a warmly lit dining room. Start dinner with escargot or calamari, order the white bean stew with lamb, pork, and duck confit for an entree, and finish with a delightful chocolate cognac mousse. Lunch and weekend brunch menus offer fresh croissants and a popular quiche with Comté cheese, which you can also take to go.

reviews.text:
What a gem! This place, although you couldn't actually go inside the store, was wonderfully charming. We got 3 of the 5 things on the menu today, and all were delicious! The longonisa especially 😍

The two sisters running this joint are incredibly friendly, and everyone at the food service bar next to us were locals/had obviously been there many many times. I am definitely adding this place to the "must revisit" list!

07/16/2022: I have always wanted to visit this food stall ever since I read an article about it. When we got there, the counter was packed. We didn't know how to order so we asked a customer. We were directed to the front of the store where we could order and pay. My friend and I each ordered the fried bangus (milkfish) and salmon sinigang (soup) plate which comes with steamed rice and pancit. We also ordered 3 pieces of Shanghai lumpia. We were then directed to the back to find a seat. Since hubby ordered a poke bowl from the vendor across the walkway, we sat at their counter since it was empty.

Our Filipino great arrived quickly. Our meals were served on melamine plates and bowls. The lumpia was skinny and long and served with sweet and sour dipping sauce. The fried bangus was crispy and truly delicious. The rice and pancit cut the richness of the fish. The salmon sinigang was simply divine. I loved the  sour tamarind flavor and the fresh leafy veggies. The soup was made with salmon collar so that gave the fish a rich, melt-in-your-mouth texture. No wonder this dish is what they're known for.

I thoroughly enjoyed my visit. I wish I could have tried their adobo and other Filipino dishes. The food is cooked in true, traditional style. This place is a total gem in Pike Place Market. I look forward to returning someday.

Tia Leila and Tia Joy were super friendly and very charming, loved seeing them engage with all their regulars! The Pork Adobo was a little bit bland and not as tender as I've had other places, but the sambal and spicy vinegar made it all quite tasty!

This place is a hidden gem! Omg it is delicious! The prices are so reasonable too. We were so lucky to meet Aunty Leila and she is so kind! We went for New Year's weekend and this was our last stop. It is a busy place so be prepared to maybe grab your dish and go sit somewhere else but we were fortunate to sit at the kitchen bar and chat with Aunty Leila. Truly so much history in this place too. We are going to make it a tradition to go here at least once whenever we are in Seattle.
I tried something new today and it was delicious! Momma was was very nice and made sure we were full! I’m a regular customer now! Thank you for the service! (Not a paid sponsor)

Oriental Mart.description: If you want to impress the tourists you (inevitably) have to take to Pike Place Market, skip pass the fish-throwers and overcrowded waterfront view joints, cross the street, and take them to this restaurant inside a grocery store. The salmon collar sinigang and succulent longanisa have made this place into an American classic. Literally, the James Beard Foundation gave Oriental Mart an America’s Classics award in 2020, and you can see why — sitting here eating adobo dishes makes you part of a long lineage of people of all classes, creeds, and colors who have eaten adobo dishes at this stainless steel lunch counter. While you ponder this, you can look at the handwritten signs cluttering the kitchen. One of them reads, “WIFI PASSWORD: TALK TO EACH OTHER”

reviews.text: Oh my goodness!! 5 starts simply because I cannot give 10! Where to start even! From the moment we walked in the door the experience was unlike any other I’ve had at a restaurant. We arrived ten minutes earlier in Seattle by bus and met an incredibly kind local couple who highly recommended this place as, “our favorite Indian restaurant in all of Seattle.” We had five luggage bags that the host, Ryan, kindly allowed us to store behind his podium at the front. We then sat down to a delightful meal full of flavor and tantalizing scents. Mara, our server was wonderful and attentive. They even brought us some chocolate cake to celebrate our recent wedding. They simply take the time to notice all the little details and care for the customer in the highest regard. We even got to meet the owner who can be seen taking time to chat with each and every one of his patrons throughout the course of the evening. Definitely will making a stop by next time we are in Seattle, and so should you! Also, try the ice cream!!! Two times voted by the people as the best dish in Seattle!!!

This fine-dine Indian restaurant has the best quality food. The misal pav that we ordered was just delicious and the best. I was happy to see the Indian rum, Old Monk on the menu that was mixed with mango flavors for the cocktail, just what an Indian needs. I also loved their kebabs, fresh and tasty. The owner is super-friendly and also came to have a conversation with us to know the reviews and talk more about us. Really loved the hospitality and the food. 10/10 recommend!

Got pre-Sounders reservations for this Pioneer Square based restaurant. They open at 5:30 and a wave of diners were sat.  Every single dish we ordered was exquisitely flavored and visually appealing.  Not your everyday Indian meal, it was a feast for both the eyes and taste buds. The service reflected the popularity of their restaurant and we arrived a bit after kick off to the match.  But still highly recommend, especially if you aren't in a time crunch. Thank goodness they are surviving the pandemic!

Translating the different flavors of Indian cuisine in prepared food is no mean feat and this restaurant succeeds in doing so. Some of the rice in the goat biryani were undercooked but the raita was delicious! The pieces of meat used were tender and juicy. The pompano fry was perfect! The service was friendly and very welcoming. The owner takes a genuine interest in his customers. The exposed brick decor beings a sense of warmth to the place.

Wow, just wow! I came in with several folks who know Indian food growing up and/or visiting India. We've been to places that call themselves authentic but somehow they get muddled in a fusion confusion. This is no fusion, and it's the real deal according to my peers. Very rarely can you sit down and witness food take someone back several years back home and bring such joy to someone. This definitely did the trick. As someone not proficient in any if the foods, I tried it all and was blown away. The flavors were on a whole different level than I'm familiar with and found myself digging right in. It's almost not fair at how good this food was, and I'll 100% be back again.

Nirmal\u2019s.description: Nirmal’s demonstrated that Seattle had an appetite for upscale Indian food; the Pioneer Square destination serves soups, biryani, and curries from a variety of regions and happily caters to pescatarians and vegetarians with items like paneer-stuffed bell pepper with spicy tomato sauce. Owners Oliver and Gita Bangera have always made sure the takeout service is as robust as the dine-in experience, although seeing the gregarious Oliver in person adds a spark to the meal.
