reviews.text:
By far the best broth I've ever tasted! I love the open concept and how bright it is in there. Parking is a little difficult but, once we arrived and entered the door, we were immediately seated. The Shrimp spring roll was okay. The noodles were a little tough and the lettuce used inside were soggy. The egg rolls were delicious and freshly fried!

Reason for the 4-star is because, it was our first time there and we had no idea that they do not bring the bill to you. We had to wave a worker down to ask for our bill. That is when we learned that you need to walk up to the bar counter and let them know what you've ordered. I'm not sure if that is a good idea because, people can truly lie about what they are ordering but, to each their own.

With that being said, overall, the food was delicious, and we will definitely be back again. This time, we will know what to do.

The restaurant space is very open and bright. We were seated quickly, and they took our order promptly. A server also offered refills before we had quite run out.

The flavors of the food were well-developed, and we enjoyed everything. The pho fries were out for the night (by 5 PM on a Thursday), but everything we did manage to get tasted great and seemed quite fresh!

Great taste of southern Vietnamese pho in a modern and lively location.

Broth was light, sweet, and savory. The ribs were tender and fell right off the bone. The tamarind chicken wings were also tender and juicy.

Portions were generous and service was excellent.

Would definitely consider this a great stop for Pho!

BEST PHO I HAVE EVER HAD!! I have had pho from a lot of different places and experienced a lot of different kinds. I have traveled to Vietnam and this tops everything in my memory. From the service to the general vibe there it could not be topped. WHEN you make the pilgrimage to this fine establishment make sure to order the Vietnamese coffee to start with. I want to end this review with another thank you to the restaurant - highest review to date.

"Wonderful and flavorful Pho at an established restaurant."

Pros:
😀 Absolutely delicious and flavorful Pho.
😀 Fast, friendly service
😀Reasonably priced and generous portion size.

Cons:
😔 Can get very busy, hence a wait time.
😔Parking is a bit limited.

🤓 Ken's Takeaway:

Went to Pho Bac for dinner with some friends. It has been a few years since I dined at the restaurant which was originally at the boat-shaped restaurant across the parking lot. Pho Bac is an established Vietnamese restaurant in the International District and it is understandable how they have fared well for so long.

The restaurant is now located in a more modern space with more of a traditional dining area. You choose your Pho and other items up front as well as making your payment. The Pho portion size is very generous and a Large can be very filling. The broth is flavorful, with many distinct nuances (beefy, light, not too oily, deep lingering taste, robust, etc). The noodles were evenly cooked and the beef slices and meatballs were tender, not bland but absorbed the broth's flavor. Adding in the extras such as the basil, bean sprouts, a spritz of lime, and condiments gives the soup another layer of subtle complexity.

Overall, the generous portions, delicious Pho recipe, easy-going atmosphere, and friendly service makes dining at Pho Bac a nice treat.

🤔 Would I go back?

Yes! Looking at the pictures, I can still remember the taste of the bowl of Pho that I had and looking forward to the next one.

Pho Bac Sup Shop.description: The Pham family’s boat-shaped Pho Bac restaurant (now called the Boat and focusing on chicken and rice) was a pioneer in Seattle’s Vietnamese dining scene. The next generation, sisters Yenvy and Quynh-Vy, have carried on the family’s legacy with aplomb at places like coffee roaster Hello Em, inspired bar Phocific Standard Time, and Pho Bac Sup Shop, which kicked off the family’s current era of expansion with modern twists to the formula in Little Saigon. Tender beef falls off the bone in aromatic bowls of pho or bun bo hue, while pho fries form a satisfying base for brisket and gravy. And the fruity and herbaceous cocktails are every bit as fragrant as the soups, leaning on mango, passionfruit, Thai basil, and Vietnamese coriander.

reviews.text: It was our first time experiencing the restaurant. It was great. Everything we ordered tasted great and the cocktails are spectacular. There are lots of people, but they try to be as attentive as possible. We dropped a spoon and they immediately brought another one. Good place!

Delicious food and atmosphere! Pretty small space, so definitely make a reservation if possible to ensure you get seated. Some of the best Filipino food I’ve had in a while. Save room for dessert if you can. I’m definitely coming back here.

Loved every dish here. The waiter was very friendly and welcoming too. My favorite was the noodles, it looked plain but so flavorful. The pork belly, crispy skin, the rest just melts in your mouth, make sure to get the garlic rice to eat with the sauce. The oysters were so fresh and juicy too. Will definitely come back again. I forgot to tell the waiter it was my birthday, I'd have loved a dessert here too. Remember to bring your vaccination cards to be seated.

Drinks were great. Food was delicious and very versatile. We did family style and loved every single dish. Eggplant and okra was my favorite along with the peanut butter short rib. They have rotating menu and I would definitely go back. The pear bourbon drink was also great.
There is so much hype around this place and now I know why. The brunch was so delicious and comforting. And the French toast was the perfect dessert.

Musang.description: Since opening in early 2020, Beacon Hill’s innovative Filipinx restaurant from star chef Melissa Miranda has developed a dynamic menu with items such as succulent short rib kare kare, smoked oysters, and mussels cooked with moringa. The homey space makes diners feel like they’re eating in a beloved family member’s living room, albeit one with killer cocktails, world-class food, and reservations that fill up quickly. Musang also gives back with charitable endeavors like a community kitchen and youth program Little Wildcats, which provides education about Filipinx recipes and culture.

reviews.text: Bar del Corso is easily at the top of our list for favorite Italian restaurants in Seattle. From the pizza to the small plates to the spritzes and cocktails, it was an amazing meal. We also loved the atmosphere - the buzz in the restaurant is warm and inviting. Make sure not to skip the warm rhubarb polenta cake for dessert!

Italian food is my favorite, and this place didn’t disappoint me! Small plates are fantastic, loved the vongole alla marinara. Special pizza was tasty and flavorful. :) Lemon olive oil cake was perfect for a dessert. Nice service as well.

Not bad, awesome ambience, rushed staff.
Wed we could not get a table but Thu worked.
I really liked the place, aery and open, one large busy room whith the pizza oven off in the corner. Out back a very pleasant patio.
We had three small plates to share, including the very popular meatballs (smoky, recommended), but all three were very salty for our tastes.
Pizza was solid, chewy crust slightly burnt, limited selections, especially for folks who don't want spicy. Loved the morel mushroom pizza special, funghi was ok with fairly American sausage (anise). I haven't cut pizza with scissors before 🙂.
Unfortunately our server was quite brief, no conversation, felt rushed the whole time, with water glasses getting refilled every minute. Post pandemic stress.
Overall a likable place with great atmosphere.

Cute spot! Was busy and I could tell they’re understaffed. Totally fine, I know times are weird rn due to Covid. Succinct menu. Amazing Negroni. Pizza had like one too many anchovies but was still bomb. It was my friend’s birthday and it felt so special. Cute date night place. Cute girls night place. Adorable overall.

Bar del Corso is wonderful! We sat on their covered patio and started with some apertivo drinks alongside the mussels and escarole salad. I am now obsessed with this salad- perfectly balanced flavors alongside crispy fresh greens. The mussels were super fresh and I loved the fennel and tomatoes in the broth. The Romana pizza followed with added mozzarella di Buffala and omg! This is the perfect pizza IMO- the crust had amazing flavor and the toppings were distributed just so to bring joy in every bite. We finished our meal with the super tender polenta cake and some amaro. It was a perfect meal with great service. Hope to be back soon!

Bar del Corso.description: Owner Jerry Corso’s expert Neapolitan-style pizzas are the primary draw for this Beacon Hill hideaway; simple toppings like spicy salami harmonize with light, airy, and slightly salty crusts. The garlic mussels, baccala fritters, and grilled octopus with corona beans are also exceptional, and reservations tend to go fast — although the restaurant recently added more sidewalk seating, great for people-watching on Beacon Avenue.

reviews.text: Very pretentious atmosphere I’ve ever experienced. On top of that had to pay mandatory 20% tips regardless of dissatisfaction. We were the first ones arrived in the restaurant and after 20 minutes the waitress told that they would run out food so we should order more. I’d like to repeat that we were the first couple in the whole restaurant. Why we were rushed to dine in instead of enjoying our meal. I think they should read their own “ego” sign hanging at the door. I was there for a special occasion at that night and I felt extremely uncomfortable. I would not recommend this place.

This is a very special place. I’m going to think twice about spending my money elsewhere, knowing that Off Alley exists. I popped my sweetbread cherry tonite ! The lamb tongue was amazing with the 2003 Clos  des Papes that we brought. We enjoyed listening to the Chef call out ‘fire the tongue’ !!

I have been to Off Alley a number of times and the staff, service and food is nothing short of exceptional. We are always greeted warmly by the owners and servers when we show up. And they everyone there is super helpful in making menu and wine choices.

The first night we went it was late and there was only a few folks left. They were beyond accommodating. They brought us everything that was left to eat and it was all delicious. No attitude. No pretension. They didn't even rush us even though it was late. I was hooked and wanted more!

Look - This is a tiny place. They are crafting food in a tiny kitchen. There is no giant fridge to store sodas. There is no room here for boring.  If you are unwilling to investigate where you are dining BEFORE you go out or not an adventurous person this may not be the place for you.  If you want creative exceptional food, a menu that changes regularly, and interesting non traditional wine pairings then you will love Off Alley.

Here it goes. I am against writing any review that isn’t positive. I am willing to update my review as long as establishment acknowledges the issue. It is never in your best interest to come off as snarky! Making your customers feel inferior is not a great feeling for anyone. When you asked us what we’d like to drink and I said a cab. Server responded with a smirk and loudly responded “a cab! Do you know our menu?”. Sorry, I do not as my friend booked the place. Then when another friend asked for a coke. Again, waiter laughed so that the people around us would noticed, and responded “no we don’t serve coke!”  Again, she’s a busy girl and did not research the menu beforehand. We’re easy people, we’ll try any place. Then when my friend asked if she could get a new plate, server responded “why what’s wrong with yours”? She said ummm too many bread crumbs and stuff on my plate. He said “sure even though you can use that bowl over there, but here I’ll get you a plate”. Too many issues with service. Being snobby is not a trend, this is Seattle…we’re casual people here. So I’m thinking maybe they act this way cause food is top notch? First three plates were light and yummy. The last few plates were overly salted. Flavors were not well balanced. It wasn’t terrible by any means, but due to behavior of the employees maybe I have higher expectations, u know, to match the food 😆 If your into just having good food and a relax night out with friends. This is not your place! Uptight!

We ordered the tasting menu because we wanted to be surprised as to what dishes we would be trying. This was hands down the best meal I've had in America- every dish was packed with multiple  levels of flavor - all beautifully balanced. My favorite was the crab bisque with fried clams! The cheese they offered as a pre- dessert was sensational cows cheese! And at the end we full, content and happy. They also paired the wine according to the dish coming out! Will be going back again soon!

Off Alley.description: No single restaurant can please everyone; at Off Alley, a 14-seat brick-walled restaurant in Columbia City, chef Evan Leichtling and partner Meghna Prakash embrace that truth. You don’t always find a meticulously seasonal chef’s-choice cooking style and a hand-written list of cool natural wines paired with punk music and attitude, but that approach is working here. The menu changes daily, so check the website to see what you might encounter, from juicy smoked mussels with celery on sourdough and whole quail with nettles in a cream sauce to salt cod with squid ink rice and a burning-hot Scotch bonnet ice cream.

reviews.text: This was the best dining experience I ever had. Food was amazing in every way and the staff was super friendly. I really enjoyed the storytelling from Kuya Aaron and the rest of the crew; listening to them talk about their own personal experiences growing up as Filipino Americans and how it influenced the dishes they made for the night. I highly recommend dining at Archipelago. I came out of this dining not just super full, but also super inspired to learn even more about the culture, also being a Filipino American. Thank you to the Archipelago Staff for the amazing work you guys are doing to the community.

Easily one of if not the best tasting menus in the greater Seattle area. Not only was the food phenomenal (as expected) but the overarching narrative and course design really put this dining experience over the top. Chef Aaron and team really have something special going on here, so definitely try to find a spot if you can! (Also 100% recommend the non-alcoholic juice pairing, was super fun and very well crafted!)

Archipelago… how to even start with such a magnificent experience? The food was unbelievable. Each dish was an experience alone. The scents, tastes, and presentation of each dish transported you to a place and time, where culture between two worlds met. The delivery of this unbelievable dining experience was so effortlessly executed in a restaurant that felt, with the welcoming chefs and crew, like being invited into someone’s home. Stories of Filipino loved ones and their journeys to and from the Pacific Northwest influenced each dish. It was an absolute treat to say the least.

Absolutely amazing culinary experience. The food was fabulous, the service on point and we even got a history lesson with every course. The wine paired perfectly with the food as well. You don't leave super full but you also don't leave hungry. The restaurant only sits 12 and the staff does a quick refresh of the bathroom after each use - towels, etc. Definitely worth the 6 month wait.

This is the kind of dining experience that whets the appetite of wanderlust, makes you want to know more, see more, do more, and be more. The food is quite simply, outstanding, but the service, spirit, and stories are breathtaking. If you get the opportunity to be welcomed home into Archipelago, jump for the chance. We cannot wait to come back and are so grateful and humbled that we got the chance to experience this place during our trip to Seattle. What a gift.

Archipelago.description: Hillman City’s nationally acclaimed Filipino American fine dining restaurant hosts intimate tasting-menu experiences that showcase the ingenuity, storytelling ability, and passion of husband-and-wife team Aaron Verzosa and Amber Manuguid. Inventive takes on anything from pandesal to sinigang and banana ketchup weave local ingredients together with the duo’s personal journeys in the area as well as those of Filipino immigrants to the Pacific Northwest, creating a unique history lesson with each dinner. The tiny restaurant’s 12 seats are normally booked out months ahead, but you can sign up for a waiting list on the website.

reviews.text:
We were eager to try this place based on the glowing reviews, and it surpassed our high expectations. It's a must visit for those nearby, and worth a trip for anyone else.

We got the Delish Combo and were happy to see all the classic favorites, plus some interesting dishes that were new to us. All amazing. We have had Ethiopian food at over a dozen places across the country, including some of the best in DC, and this has to be my favorite.

The staff and owner were also wonderful, which made the whole experience that much better. Plus they have gluten free injera! Can't recommend highly enough.

Amazing service! Beautiful design choice and lovely hosts. The first time I had Ethiopian food was with my friend Sam who is featured in these pictures. He flew all the way from Brazil and has been in America for 5 years. We both loved this place! Brought a huge party of people and the piece point for the quality of food was literally amazing.

Time at about 6:30pm there wasn't much of a wait for a huge party and I'd honestly go back there again! Thank you for the meal. Only thing I hope for is Sambusa

I did a lot of "research" online to find the "best" Ethiopian restaurant in town, and then settled on Delish. And this must be one of the few times where I was satisfied with my decision.

First of all shout out to them for holding our table on a busy  Saturday afternoon even though we were late. Loved the ambience and the pleasant attitude of the hosts. Vegetarian and tasty are usually a rare combination to come across, but their Veg platter knocks it out of the park. I thought I will have to order one more Injera, but their serving was so filling I didn't have to:). Now coming to the Coffee - I swear by the South Indian Filter Coffee, but the Ethiopian version was so good, I had 3 cups! Add to that the ceremonial feel with the colorful cups and incense. Would definitely recommend to anyone interested in trying out Ethiopian cuisine. It was totally worth the drive.

Finally, a good  Ethiopian restaurant in Seattle! Been looking for one for a long time. Loved the food here, we tried the veggie platter here, all the items on the platter were delicious, injera was just perfect as well.  Their veggie spring roll was unique, not what we were expecting. The tomato salad was a bit too tangy for me.

Only disappointment was that they had very option for chicken. Their tea is a must try as well. It’s spiced (3 different  spices) water with Lipton tea bag. The spiced water itself was so flavorful that I dint even bother using the tea bag.

Place was clean and staff was super friendly. They also have traditional Ethiopian seating.

We went to check this place out after reading about it in the Seattle Eater 38. It’s got a casual, cozy, hole in the wall vibe. The food was delicious. We got the veggie and meat combo platters. Everything was excellent - we will be back!

Delish Ethiopian Cuisine.description: A relative newcomer to the vibrant Hillman City Ethiopian scene, Delish Ethiopian Cuisine has a bar area and a comfortable atmosphere in which husband and wife Delish Lemma and Amy Abera of Addis Ababa share recipes passed down from Abera’s mother and grandmother. Run the meat-free section of the menu with the 10-item veggie combo or try succulent beef tibs pan-fried in garlic, butter, onion, and berbere spice. Delish also offers an Ethiopian coffee ceremony for five or more diners.

reviews.text: We came here after seeing all the great reviews. It was good food with good flavor but nothing out of this world. The reason I am giving this a two star is because I ordered a burrito which was like $12 and it was mostly filled with rice. I took pictures as I ate it to show. If I’m paying for a burrito I expect some meat in there as the prices are quite high. I was extremely disappointed. My husband said that the chicken tacos and adobada tacos were meh and the asada tacos were good. The horchata was watered down quite a bit but it was still ok. If you go here beware with ordering things which you cannot see inside. They might just fill it up with rice and beans.

I'm from Texas and was skeptical about one of the most highly acclimated Seattle taco spots. Taqueria la Fondita delivered! These are solid tacos by any standard. I understand the love they get. Try the asada and pastor tacos. They're both great choices to explore more traditional styles of street tacos.

I usually love this place but can’t stand being taken for a fool. I ordered lengua tacos and they threw some lengua on there but filled the rest with cabeza. Lengua is more expensive than cabeza so I feel scammed. You can clearly see the two different types of meat. I paid $38 for 8 tacos. That’s crazy. They been skimping on the meat lately. Probably saves them a ton of costs.

Creen que uno es menso.
solid tacos, horchata is nice and refreshing. generous with the toppings. i got pescado and lengua tacos - both nicely seasoned. easy and nothing pretentious ! 👍🏽
Best chicken tacos in Seattle and trust me I’ve tried a lot of places.

Taqueria la Fondita.description: This enormously popular White Center food truck (with additional locations in Greenwood and Tacoma) has been a steady presence for years that gives a lot of bang for the buck. Plates pile up with carne asada, adobada, and lengua tacos; be sure to add to the experience by requesting extra grilled mini-onions and spicy serrano peppers. There’s also a small covered patio next to the truck that provides a comfortable place to dig in while the food’s piping hot.

reviews.text:
Wow! So many good things to say about TOMO.

1. The customer service was out of this world. I’ve never felt so accommodated and a priority as I did here. They went above and beyond to ensure we could take our time and enjoy a lovely evening at our own pace. They were observant, incredibly kind and you can tell how healthy of an atmosphere they allow for their team to thrive.

2. The food - wow. So beautiful, so creative and the flavors all complimented each other without overpowering anything else. There was one item that was a little out of the box for my pallet and they kindly brought out a vegetarian option for me to enjoy.

3. The restaurant- the vibe was so minimalistic, calming and inviting. They pay attention to every detail from the silverware to the wall color.

Could not recommend TOMO enough! Thank you for a wonderful evening.

Vibe- great upscale hip vibe, no complaints.

Food- small dishes, cooked perfectly, we were adequately full when we left.

Service- it was good but not quite 5-star hotel or fancy restaurant in a big city caliber. It was a casual/cool/pleasant interaction. Upon check in and seating we were given directions to a closet where we could hang our coats, but no one offered to take our coats for us. We had to ask another staff member if we could order some drinks after sitting for about 15m We would have tipped 20%

Overall: We weren’t really sure what the hype and long reservation wait were for to be honest. We both agreed d good food but it seemed overpriced since we spent $300 for two people and we’re not sure what made it so expensive. They have a set menu but charge you extra for bread. They charge you 22% for tip then tax you on that charge so be prepared for a 30% addition to your bill. We just feel like we overpaid and probably will not visit again.

Ok, I wish I could give 0 stars on here. I don’t get why I needed to pay an automatic 22% tip (for two) as a requirement and got served ridiculous food. I had to wait for 40 min for one of my dishes, so I thought it would be the main entree -- but it was grilled asparagus. The funny thing is that a table next to us who came long after us were served the same courses at the same time as us, as if the chef were waiting to cook everything all at once. Do you think the design of food is creative? Well, if you think so, you’d better explore more food. I swear you could see better plating and creativity of food at a more reasonable price elsewhere. Also, I have no idea which part of the food served is inspired by Japanese food as the name (and story) of the restaurant implies. (Don’t get me wrong. I wasn't expecting we’d get served sushi). I had a couple of different servers but no one asked us how’s the food or if we needed anything. I don't think I should pay a good tip for just mediocre service, pretending that the restaurant is upscale.

They have limited availability but it was worth  it! The cocktails are some of the best ones we have ever had. Not too sweet and very flavorful! The food portions are a little small. The entrance is very interesting - you would never guess what’s inside. Recommended experience!

I've been eager to visit TOMO for a while now and to be honest, it was probably not worth the hype nor the long reservation wait.

I thought the atmosphere, and service were great. No complaints. The time between plates took a while, but other than the long dinner service, it was fine. I love the bar area and we had dinner for 4 people so company was great. Took 2 hours from beginning to end.

Food is where I felt could have been improved. I thought that for the price, you'd either get decent portions or extremely elevated and "complex" flavors which the menu failed on. There are 5 dishes and I only enjoyed two of them that felt unique or tasty. The middle 3 (fish, lamb and salad) were all average. We didn't get the wine pairing but thought the cocktails were good. Not mindblowing, but good. Overall, it was $85 pp plus $20 for each drink and we didn't get any add-ons. There's an auto gratuity of 22%.

Tomo.description: The name Tomo means “friend” in Japanese and pays homage to Tomoko Ishiwata Bristol, the grandmother of former Canlis chef Brady Williams. Book a seat inside the lauded chef’s intimate White Center restaurant for coursed dinners of hyper-seasonal Pacific Northwest cuisine like pork collar with squash, fermented radish chawanmushi, and sweet potato with miso caramel. No reservation? The patio and bar welcome walk-ins for a la carte bites like vegetable curry buns and an excellent selection of wine and cocktails.

reviews.text: Embarrassed to say we have lived her for 3 years and never tried this place until tonight.. wow! This place is as legit as it gets and really tastes authentic. We had the mole enchiladas with pork and 4 tacos and devoured it all. Next time we will be trying the highly rated molotes. Lovely staff and reasonable prices for what you get. If you haven't visited here yet, make sure you plan a stop soon!

My husband and I decided to give this place a shot and I can honestly say that I was not disappointed! The first I have to say is the customer service is so amazing! The food is really good and my husband loved the salsa , I don’t care for Smokey salsas so I passed on the sauce but all in all it was very good food! We got a carne asada burrito and molotes which were fantastic! They are a little pricey for Mexican food but I still recommend everyone try it! We will definitely be back.

Wow, really good tacos. I just tried this place because of an instagram post I saw. I had no idea it was there. Super flavorful tacos. I had vegi and chicken mole. Seriously, close to the best tacos I have ever eaten. I can not wait to go back and try other things on the menu! I sat outside in the back. Really sweet outside area. Nothing fancy, but sweet.  I had 4 tacos, chips and guacamole and a beer and it was $25 +tip.

Sweet little hole in the wall in Burien.  They had one last order of empanadas with shrimp and crab left and I scooped it up.  The filling was chock full of shrimp and crab in a delicate white sauce.  The plating was beautiful.  It was topped with shredded cabbage, cherry tomatoes and two sauces.  I was offered and took a small container of chipotle salsa which was great on top.  It came with chips and salsa and a plate of rice and beans.  The black beans were incredibly tasty - earthy and soft, seasoned just right; I couldn't stop eating them.
Loved everything I tasted! We ordered the chile relleno and enchiladas de mole. I’m so happy to add another place to my list of restaurants with authentic Mexican food!

El Cabrito.description: After five years as a food truck, El Cabrito became a brick-and-mortar restaurant on Burien’s Ambaum Boulevard in 2019, with a few seats indoors and some covered tables on a back patio. Owner Leticia Sánchez started making moles with her grandmother in Oaxaca when she was 5 years old, and these years of experience show in dishes like the expertly balanced mole coloradito that pools around pork enchiladas and the molotes (fried masa dumplings filled with potato and chorizo) drowned in smoky morita pepper and avocado salsas, all presented on brightly hued ceramics. El Cabrito also serves specials like rockfish ceviche, tamales, and blue crab empanadas.

reviews.text: I travel all over the United States for work, and this is one of the best, if not the best Thai food I’ve had. I also enjoyed the atmosphere which made me feel like I was in Thailand. The service was also outstanding.
First time I tried Thai foods. Foods were delicious and surrounded with friendly stuff. I might go to visit to Vashon because of this restaurant .

We have ordered takeout 2x while visiting Vashon and both times the food and value were excellent. The fact this is the only Thai place in town could easily mean they could just do mediocre food and people would have no other choice. But for locals and visitors it is all top notch!

Will always be a 2nd home to me!
I love the staff, the food, and the atmosphere.
My favorite dishes are the Gaeng Massaman with beef, Gaeng Faak Thong with fried tofu, and Grapao Gap Kaidao with fried tofu. The Phad Thai is really the main show though. The prices reflect the portion sizes.
This was an amazing restaurant. Make sure to order Pad Thai. They mix everything together at your table and it's delicious. Highly recommend!

May Kitchen and Bar.description: Vashon Island’s celebrated Thai restaurant is so good that many Seattleites take the ferry over just to sample the food. Owner May Chaleoy’s flavors shine brightly in entrees like whole fried trout alongside mango salad flecked with mint and cashews as well as satisfying appetizers like grilled pork skewers marinated in yellow curry. She also offers versions of ubiquitous Thai dishes with elegant twists, like pad thai served with turnips and banana blossom or tom yum soup with oyster mushrooms.

reviews.text: I haven’t had much Guatemalan food before, so I don’t claim to be an expert on the cuisine. That being said, I really enjoyed everything I tried here, especially the beet salad and the pupusas. I visited with one other person and we were able to have a very filling dinner with a wide variety of flavors by splitting many different small plates. The atmosphere is very casual and the servers are friendly. I also enjoyed my first Guatemalan beer, which was quite refreshing and paired well with dinner.

This place was great! I’m so happy that finally I get to eat some Guatemalan food. I just wished that when we ordered the appetizer, it would have come out before the food, that’s why is call an appetizer. I hope that down the road they make More authentic Guatemalan food. I will definitely come again and again

We stop by there on our way to Enumclaw.
Friendly service, casual vibe and good food.
We had tacos, steaks, horchata and chips.
Beans with chips are very nice. Also homemade tortillas is fantastic.
We would like to visit there again.
I've never tried Guatemala food before. The food here is very tasty and well presented. Highly recommended.
Absolutely delicious. Everything was fantastic. I really want to come back and try their breakfast dishes.

Antigua Guatemala Restaurant.description: Wilfredo and Elvi Reyes run Antigua, one of the Seattle area’s few Guatemalan restaurants, decorated with bright photos of their home country: a yellow clocktower on an arch in the country’s old capital, the volcanic lake Atitlán, and the resplendent national bird, the quetzal. Since then, diners have flocked to this Kent strip mall to drink micheladas and eat comforting pre-colonial dishes like banana leaf-wrapped corn tamales filled with loroco and chipilín (indigenous Central American plants) while upbeat salsa music plays. The Spanish-influenced, slow-grilled churrasco chapin strip, marinated with tomato and garlic, is one of the best steaks around, and the tostada topped with chow mein (a popular Guatemalan street food) neatly contrasts crispy tostada and soft noodle. You’ll also find Guatemalan breakfast foods, a comforting atol de elote in the colder months, and fried plantains stuffed with a sweet bean mixture.
